map_node.indicator_name: PM<sub>2.5</sub>-Attributable Respiratory Hospitalizations (Adults 20 Yrs and Older)
map_node.indicator_description: Estimating hospitalizations that can be linked to PM2.5 is a way to understand how air pollution impacts public health.

dataset.how_calculated: Estimate is based on the number of hospitalizations for respiratory causes associated with the difference in air quality for indicator years relative to modeled natural background. Estimate is calculated using the acute risk of hospitalizations for all respiratory causes from the Moolgavkar 2000 study conducted on Los Angeles residents between 20-64 years of age and the Zanobetti et al 2009 study in 26 US communities of residents over 65 years of age. Neighborhood estimates expressed as annual cases per 100,000 residents over 20 years of Age.
dataset.source: USEPA AQS; Moolgavkar SH (2000); Zanobetti et.al.(2009)
dataset.discription: New York State Statewide Planning and Research Cooperative System (SPARCS); US Census,USEPA Air Quality System; Moolgavkar SH (2000) Inhal Toxicol 12(Supp 4):7590; Zanobetti etal.(2009) Environ Hlth 8:58. doi:10.1186/1476-069X-8-58

show_disparities_node.disparitiesPagetext: When population health or the quality of living environments varies by population characteristics such as income or race, there is disparity. One way to visualize disparity is to chart indicators of health or environment across levels of neighborhood poverty. We categorized neighborhoods as high, medium or low poverty. Then we took the median of the neighborhood-specific values in each category. The median is the middle of the sorted group of values.
